fields.public_field_1_en: Mayor! You have a call. One of your staff members is calling to talk about the growing problem with housing affordability in Bayville.
fields.public_field_2_en: Answer the call

fields.public_field_1_en: Chief of Staff
fields.public_field_2_en: The average family today spends around 25 percent of its income on housing, and there are many families that spend much more. Building affordable housing can be expensive and the city’s budget is already stretched, but something needs to be done. If we do not advance any new policies, the average family could be priced out of Bayville within the next few decades.
fields.public_field_3_en: Go to your Housing Plan!

fields.public_field_2_en: Raise new revenue to fund affordable housing production and preservation
fields.public_field_3_en: Generate new funds to build affordable housing and preserve existing affordable units through fees or taxes.
fields.public_field_4_en: This would provide a continuous stream of funds to address the need for affordable housing over time.
fields.public_field_4_meta_description: Strategy 1 pros
fields.public_field_5_en: New taxes and fees could increase the cost of living, which could be harmful to low-income families already struggling to afford daily necessities.
fields.public_field_8_en: Require 10 to 20 percent of all new housing to be affordable
fields.public_field_9_en: Require developers to set aside 10 to 20 percent of all newly constructed units to be rented at a subsidized rate.
fields.public_field_10_en: The costs of building affordable units would be paid by developers, instead of by the city or nonprofit groups.
fields.public_field_11_en: The required subsidy is only effective in a booming housing market where more housing is built overall.
fields.public_field_15_en: Strengthen renter protections to prevent large rent increases and restrict evictions without a strong justification.
fields.public_field_16_en: This strategy shields renters from large or unexpected rent increases and unjustified, no-fault evictions, providing renters with more stable housing conditions.
fields.public_field_17_en: Limiting rental housing profitability could reduce the overall supply of units for rent.
fields.public_field_20_en: Do not adopt a strategy to address housing affordability
fields.public_field_21_en: Choose not to adopt any of the proposed strategies and continue the status quo. In Bayville, this means watching the existing supply of affordable housing units and vouchers that subsidize housing in the private market shrink, leaving residents waiting for state or federal investments to fund new affordable housing.

fields.public_field_1_en: raise new revenue to fund affordable housing production and preservation!
fields.public_field_3_en: Implementing this strategy in the Bay Area is estimated to produce between 400 and 600 new permanently affordable rental units each year. That’s around 11,000 to 17,000 units between now and 2050. Thousands more already affordable units were maintained and remained affordable.

That’s around 70,000 to 100,000 units between now and 2050. However, this policy only improved affordability for those that were able to move to these new units and did not help people afford to stay in their existing homes.

fields.public_field_1_en: Resident
fields.public_field_2_en: Our city owns some land that is sitting vacant, with no plans for future use. Since we already own that land, building housing there would be cheaper and faster than if we had to first find a site and buy it. We could build there ourselves or sell the land to an affordable housing developer.

Storefronts have been empty for months, and retail is in a prolonged decline as more people choose to shop online. We could work with the mall owners to turn these sites into vibrant neighborhoods with a mix of housing, workplaces and shops!

fields.public_field_5_en: The city could generate more tax revenue if they used the public land for other uses, such as an office park.
fields.public_field_9_en: Work with property owners to redevelop vacant and under-performing shopping centers into mixed-income neighborhoods.
fields.public_field_10_en: These sites are often located on large lots near existing transportation routes, making them ideal candidates for redevelopment.
fields.public_field_11_en: Convincing property owners and all of their tenants to vacate so that the malls could be redeveloped may require additional time. If even one tenant refuses to leave, redeveloping the site would not be possible.

fields.public_field_10_en: This policy gives more people access to transit while also providing new riders for transit systems and more patrons for local businesses near transit corridors.

fields.public_field_1_en: You get to City Hall and sit down at your desk. You hear a knock at the door - it’s the city manager here for your weekly meeting. Today’s topic: policies to influence the location of jobs.
fields.public_field_2_en: Open the door.

fields.public_field_1_en: City Manager
fields.public_field_2_en: Over time, parts of our city have become primarily residential, while jobs are concentrated in downtown. Every morning, waves of workers travel from the residential neighborhoods to their workplaces downtown, resulting in traffic congestion and crowded buses and trains. Meanwhile, trains and roads going from downtown to the residential neighborhoods during the morning commute are almost completely empty! If more neighborhoods had a mix of jobs and housing, residents would have better commutes.
fields.public_field_3_en: Go to your Economy Plan!

fields.public_field_1_en: Which approach would you take to promote a more balanced distribution of jobs and housing?
fields.public_field_2_en: Explore strategies
Limit new office construction in jobs-rich locations
fields.public_field_3_en: Limit the number of new office buildings that can be built each year in areas with many more jobs than residents.
fields.public_field_4_en: This could make office space in high-demand areas more expensive, encouraging employers to seek cheaper land or rents elsewhere within the region.
fields.public_field_4_meta_description: Strategy 1 pros
fields.public_field_5_en: Placing a limit on where office space can be built could lead to some employers moving out of the city.
fields.public_field_8_en: Create incubator programs in economically challenged neighborhoods
fields.public_field_9_en: Provide resources to support the creation of businesses by low- and moderate-income people in communities with limited job opportunities.
fields.public_field_10_en: This strategy could spur economic activity, create jobs and keep wealth circulating within the economically challenged communities.
fields.public_field_11_en: Small businesses need time to grow and mature before they can provide a substantial number of jobs.
fields.public_field_14_en: Do not adopt a strategy for promoting a more balanced distribution of jobs and housing
fields.public_field_15_en: Choose not to adopt any of the proposed strategies and rely on existing regulations to determine where new office or commercial development occurs.

However, some businesses have threatened to move jobs to a neighboring city where downtown office space is available, leading residents to worry this policy could damage Bayville’s economy. Implementing this strategy in the Bay Area is estimated to shift thousands of jobs to large cities in Alameda County, leading to a more balanced distribution of homes and jobs.

fields.public_field_1_en: BackToWork
fields.public_field_2_en: Many working parents can’t afford childcare and have to put their careers on hold because of it.

fields.public_field_7_en: We don’t have enough trained people to fill the construction jobs we have today, much less meet the increased future demand.
fields.public_field_8_en: Investing in training the construction workforce will help us keep up and will provide more middle-wage family-supporting jobs.
fields.public_field_10_en: Many people in our city today are part-time or freelance workers.
fields.public_field_11_en: They like the flexibility, but most of these jobs don’t provide benefits like health insurance the way many full-time jobs do.
fields.public_field_12_en: We should require employers to pay for a fair share of worker benefits.

fields.public_field_1_en: Which workforce policy will you implement?
fields.public_field_2_en: Explore strategies
Provide portable benefits for part-time and freelance workers
fields.public_field_3_en: Support state legislation requiring companies that rely on part-time or freelance workers to contribute benefits in proportion to the hours worked.
fields.public_field_4_en: This would reduce the individual costs of obtaining insurance for thousands of part-time or freelance workers. A similar policy was recently passed by the California legislature, and other Bay Area cities have passed related legislation requiring companies pay this type of worker an hourly rate set at a living wage.
fields.public_field_4_meta_description: Strategy 1 pros
fields.public_field_5_en: When faced with the costs of contributing to benefits for part-time or freelance workers, employers could choose to outsource, automate or eliminate these jobs instead.
fields.public_field_8_en: Expand childcare support for low-income families
fields.public_field_9_en: Provide reduced-cost childcare for families with children under 5 years old that earn less than the $45,000 per year, enabling parents to return to work or attend school without worrying about the cost of childcare.
fields.public_field_10_en: This strategy would allow thousands of parents to return to work or school and would benefit children through education.
fields.public_field_11_en: While investing in early-childhood education pays for itself in higher tax revenues over time, this strategy has a high cost per child in the short term.
fields.public_field_15_en: Partner with community colleges and construction companies to provide training, apprenticeships and incentives to prepare people for middle-wage construction industry jobs.
fields.public_field_16_en: This would address the current deficit in the construction workforce, training the workers needed to build new housing and maintain infrastructure.
fields.public_field_17_en: This program could be seen as subsidizing the training costs of privately-owned construction companies.

fields.public_field_1_en: After another eventful day as mayor, it is time to head home. It’s evening rush hour, and your train is packed as usual. You squeeze into an open spot and the doors close. You start up a conversation with the person standing next to you.
fields.public_field_2_en: What do they say?

fields.public_field_1_en: Resident
fields.public_field_2_en: Have you noticed how during rush hour, trains and buses are standing room only and traffic congestion is bumper to bumper? If we don’t invest in our transit system now and our city keeps growing, residents and workers will have an even harder time getting where they need to be. You’re the mayor - what are you going to do for public transportation?
fields.public_field_3_en: Go to your Transportation Plan!

fields.public_field_1_en: What’s your top priority for investing in public transit?
fields.public_field_2_en: Explore strategies
Improve the reliability and frequency of the existing rail network
fields.public_field_3_en: Improve the speed and frequency of our existing rail system through projects like buying new train cars or building subways in the place of existing street-level light rail.
fields.public_field_4_en: This strategy would make transit a more attractive option by increasing speed and frequency.
fields.public_field_4_meta_description: Strategy 1 pros
fields.public_field_5_en: Selecting this strategy means that you will have limited funds to extend rail service to new communities in the future.
fields.public_field_9_en: Connect more neighborhoods and communities directly to the rail system by extending existing lines or building new lines.
fields.public_field_10_en: This strategy would increase the number of destinations directly accessible by rail.
fields.public_field_11_en: As the length of the rail system grows, the cost to operate and maintain the system grows as well, which means you will have fewer resources for new projects moving forward.
fields.public_field_14_en: Build and operate a next-generation Bus Rapid Transit network
fields.public_field_15_en: Invest in developing a more extensive Bus Rapid Transit (BRT) network, including the creation of bus-only lanes that let buses travel faster on congested roads and enhanced stations that let passengers board more quickly.
fields.public_field_16_en: This strategy can be implemented relatively quickly and at a lower cost than rail transit.
fields.public_field_17_en: High quality Bus Rapid Transit operates in its own dedicated lane, which means the number of lanes for personal automobiles would be reduced on roads with BRT.
fields.public_field_20_en: Do not adopt a strategy for investing in public transportation
fields.public_field_21_en: Choose not to adopt any of the proposed strategies and rely on the existing transportation system to serve the public.

fields.public_field_1_en: The first item on your agenda today is a debate hosted by the economics club at the local community college. They will be discussing their ideas for the future of transportation pricing and payment - just in time for you to consider their ideas for your transportation plan!
fields.public_field_2_en: Hear what they have to say.

fields.public_field_1_en: Student
fields.public_field_2_en: There are so many transportation options these days, and no single app that includes them all. We have bike share, scooter share, ridehailing services and public transit - plus, who knows what new type of transportation will show up next week!? Getting around would be so much easier if we had a free smartphone app that showed all of the transportation options and let you pay for them with one click.
fields.public_field_3_en: See what the next person has to say.

fields.public_field_1_en: Student
fields.public_field_2_en: Did you know that after housing, transportation is the second largest cost in most people’s budgets? I think we should make public transit free for low-income people. That way, everyone could get to where they need to be without having to consider transit costs.
fields.public_field_3_en: Keep listening.

fields.public_field_1_en: Student
fields.public_field_2_en: Traffic congestion is a serious problem in our city. The Express Lanes that exist on some highways in our city help, providing people with the option to bypass traffic if they pay a toll. If we expanded on this idea and charged a small fee for every mile driven on the highway, maybe more people would consider carpooling or taking transit. We could give a discount to carpoolers or people traveling outside of rush hour, and we would be able to reinvest the fees in improving roadways and expanding transit options.
fields.public_field_3_en: Go to your Transportation Plan!

fields.public_field_1_en: Which pricing and payment strategy do you want to implement?
fields.public_field_2_en: Explore strategies
Develop a single app for all mobility options
fields.public_field_3_en: Create a free smartphone app that shows users all of their transportation options, including public transit, ridehailing and shared mobility, for any given trip and lets them pay for their trip from one account, which can be linked to a debit card or loaded with cash at a kiosk.
fields.public_field_4_en: This strategy could improve the transportation experience for users of all types of transportation.
fields.public_field_4_meta_description: Strategy 1 pros
fields.public_field_5_en: By making ridehail services easier to view and pay for, this strategy may encourage transit users to switch to ridehail services, resulting in increased traffic congestion.
fields.public_field_8_en: Provide free transit to low-income riders
fields.public_field_9_en: Work with transit operators to create a free transit program for qualifying lower-income residents.
fields.public_field_10_en: This strategy could reduce financial barriers to public transit, helping lower-income riders get around.
fields.public_field_11_en: Free passes will cut revenues for cash-starved transit agencies, while potentially leading to overcrowding and higher maintenance costs.
fields.public_field_14_en: Apply time-of-day tolls on all freeways
fields.public_field_15_en: Apply a toll on all Bay Area freeways that varies based on the number of miles driven, with discounts for carpoolers and travel outside of peak demand periods.
fields.public_field_16_en: This strategy could encourage more people to shift when they travel or choose to carpool or take transit instead of driving alone, while also generating revenue for transit and active transportation.
fields.public_field_17_en: Charging a per-mile toll would have a financial impact on drivers, especially ones that are low-income.
fields.public_field_20_en: Do not adopt a strategy to change the pricing and payment of transportation services
fields.public_field_21_en: Choose not to adopt any of the proposed strategies and rely on existing policies that determine the cost of driving and public transit and how these costs are paid.

fields.public_field_1_en: develop a single app for all mobility options!
fields.public_field_3_en: Residents are excited to try the new app and transit operators are hopeful that ridership will increase. Vienna, the capital of Austria, recently released a similar platform for use by its residents. After one year, 21 percent of users reported reducing their car usage. Implementing this strategy in the Bay Area could have a similar impact.

fields.public_field_1_en: Now it is time to bike over to your next meeting. Unfortunately, you have a flat tire, but you’re in luck! There is a bike shop just down the street. As you are checking out, the shop owner starts talking to you about the active transportation section of your transportation plan.
fields.public_field_2_en: I’m listening.

fields.public_field_1_en: Bike Shop Owner
fields.public_field_2_en: Did you know that around twenty percent of all trips made in our city today are under three miles? That’s a twenty minute ride on a bike or electric scooter. Even so, only ten percent of these short trips are made by bike. How is your transportation plan going to encourage more people to leave their cars at home?
fields.public_field_3_en: Go to your Transportation Plan!

fields.public_field_1_en: What is your strategy to encourage more residents to leave their cars at home for short trips?
fields.public_field_2_en: Explore strategies
Build a network of safe paths for bicycles, e-bikes, scooters and pedestrians
fields.public_field_3_en: Fund a complete network of off-street paths, protected bike lanes and sidewalks for walking, biking and scootering.
fields.public_field_4_en: This strategy would reduce exposure to auto traffic and make biking and walking safer and more comfortable, resulting in better health outcomes for your residents.
fields.public_field_4_meta_description: Strategy 1 pros
fields.public_field_5_en: Building some physically separated bike lanes could require removing on-street parking or auto lanes.
fields.public_field_8_en: Lower speed limits to reduce roadway injuries and fatalities
fields.public_field_9_en: Work with the state government to pass measures reducing the speed limits on freeways and select local streets, reducing the likelihood of fatality or serious injury for drivers, passengers, cyclists and pedestrians.
fields.public_field_10_en: Reducing automobile speeds could result in fewer fatalities and serious injuries on Bayville’s roads, while also reducing greenhouse gas emissions by requiring vehicles to travel at more fuel-efficient speeds.
fields.public_field_11_en: Enforcing speed limit reductions will be difficult, not to mention unpopular with many drivers.
fields.public_field_15_en: Increase the size of the existing bike share and scooter share system and make it free to all residents, while providing free shuttle service for those who cannot use these services due to mobility limitations.
fields.public_field_16_en: Electric bikes and scooters can be expensive. This strategy removes the cost barrier to these forms of transportation, allowing more people to use them.
